  "prompt": "What traffic laws in Dominica are particularly hard for foreign drivers to get used to?",
  "response": "Foreign drivers may find certain traffic laws and driving customs in Dominica difficult to adjust to. Here are a few notable ones:\n\n1. **Driving on the Left**: Dominica follows the British system of driving on the left side of the road. This can be challenging for drivers from countries where driving is done on the right side.\n\n2. **Narrow and Winding Roads**: Many of Dominica\u2019s roads are narrow, winding, and hilly. These roads can be difficult to navigate, especially for drivers accustomed to wide and straight highways.\n\n3. **Use of Roundabouts**: Roundabouts are common in Dominica, and navigating them can be tricky for those unfamiliar with the rules and etiquette associated with these traffic circles.\n\n4. **Road Conditions**: Some roads may be poorly maintained, with potholes and uneven surfaces, requiring careful driving and constant attention.\n\n5. **Signage**: Road signs may not always be clear or plentiful, and relying on GPS navigation can sometimes be unreliable due to the country\u2019s terrain and infrastructure.\n\n6. **Local Driving Customs**: Local driving practices, such as honking to signal intent or to let another driver go ahead, may be unfamiliar and require time to understand and adopt.\n\n7. **Pedestrian and Animal Crossings**: Drivers must be cautious and watch for pedestrians and animals that may suddenly cross the road, particularly in rural areas.\n\n8. **Speed Limits**: Speed limits may vary and sometimes are not clearly posted, requiring drivers to be vigilant and adapt their speed accordingly.\n\n9. **Licensing Requirements**: Foreign drivers may need to obtain a local driving permit or an International Driving Permit (IDP) to legally drive in Dominica, which can be a new requirement for those not accustomed to it.\n\nAdjusting to these driving conditions and regulations can take time and patience for foreign drivers.",
